:::summary
Galaxies are vast systems of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter bound together by gravity — the fundamental building blocks of the large-scale structure of the universe. Our own Milky Way galaxy contains an estimated 200 to 400 billion stars, and the observable universe contains hundreds of billions of galaxies. When the Psalmist wrote that the heavens declare the glory of God, he could not have imagined the scale of creation we now know — yet the sentiment is only more true in light of what modern astronomy has revealed.
